    <text>
        <body>
            <div type="edition">
        <ab>
                    <lb n="1"/>ἄρξαι, χεὶρ ἀγαθή, <lb n="2"/>καλὰ γράμματα <lb n="3"/>καὶ στίχον
                    ὀρθόν. <lb n="4"/>καὶ <choice>
                        <orig>σοὶ</orig>
                        <reg>σύ</reg>
                    </choice> μιμοῦ.</ab></div>
            <div type="translation">
            <p>Begin, good hand, fine letters and a straight line (of writing).</p></div>

            <div type="commentary">
                <p>The text records a typical school exercise. The teacher has supplied a four-line
                    model at the top of the tablet through a dactylic hexameter which is attested on
                    several other school tablets, followed by an exhortation to imitate it on the
                    last line of the tablet. The student then repeats the exercise several times
                    below. Each successive copy is taken not from the teacher's original but from
                    the version immediately above it, with the result that any error introduced by
                    the student is preserved and propagated through all subsequent lines. This
                    feature makes such tablets especially valuable for tracing the transmission of
                    scribal mistakes within a single hand.</p></div>
            

